published in an annotated edition by Frank E. Comparato (Fray Andres de Avendano y Loyola: Relation of Two Trips .... , 1987). While that translation is largely satisfactory, it does contain errors that com­promise its reliability. 
Mayanists will therefore welcome Vayhinger­Scheer's careful, scholarly transcription, first published in 1996 and reissued in this edition. Her work is well informed by her broader knowledge of Avendano and the colonial world in which he lived, by her knowledge of the colonial Yucatec Mayan language (which Avendano spoke and sometimes inserted in his text, both in Yucatec and closely related ltza forms), and by her familiarity with the nuances of colonial Spanish writing style. At the time of publication, she was preparing a graduate thesis on Avendano, since com­pleted, at the University of Bonn. 
Following a useful preface by Nikolai Grube, Vayhinger-Scheer provides an introduction detailing the known history of the original manuscript and its publication history, an explanation of her methods of transcription and recording, biographical notes on Avendano, and selected details on the historical signifi­cance of his account. The non-annotated transcription that follows is accurate and literal, although she adopts modern Spanish orthography and introduces punctua­tion for ease of reading (always indicated by bracket­ing). The original spelling of Maya names and terms is retained. The folio numbering is indicated in the text, allowing specialists to compare the transcription with the original manuscript with ease. Avendano's original sketch map of Lago Peten ltza is included, along with a transcribed version. The index of Maya and Spanish personal names, toponyms, and terms makes the work even more useful to researchers. 
I made ample use of this account in a recent book on Spanish-Itza interactions (Jones, The Conquest of the Last Maya Kingdom, 1998). Vayhinger-Scheer, who read the entire manuscript of that book prior to publica­tion, made valuable comments on it that informed the final revision. Chapter 3, in which I offer a tentative reconstruction of ltza political and social organization, draws heavily on a list of Itza political officials dictated to Avendano while he was at Nojpeten. Chapters 7 and 8 contain a detailed analysis of Avendano's two trips, including, in the latter chapter, an analysis of his per­sonal encounters with the Itza king, Ajaw Kan Ek', and other members of the ltza nobility during January 14-19, 1696. I attempt there to deconstruct his account of his experiences at Nojpeten in light of the complex political maneuvering and public as well as covert diplomacy that characterized the period preceding the military conquest of the Itzas. 
As with all primary colonial sources, Avendano's account must be read and interpreted with great care. It is above all a political essay whose primary aim was to justify Franciscan claims that their order had already initiated the Christian conversion of the Itzas and should alone be permitted to provide future missionary services to them. That aim turned out to be futile, as the Franciscans failed to gain support of the local colonial government, who turned to the secular clergy instead. Many of Avendano's ethnographic details may be taken at or near face value, such as descriptions of architec­ture, geography, location of settlements along his travel route, crops, clothing styles, and bodily adornment. Many others, however, must be examined much more critically, especially his exaggerated accounts of perfor­mativity (his own and the ltzas'), his claims concerning ltza gender and sexuality and their religious rituals and "idols," and the significance of ltza k'atun prophecies as a portent of their inevitable surrender. His text is only a small part of a vast contemporary written discourse on the conquest and subjugation of the Itzas and their Maya neighbors and should be read in that wider light. 
